  'ea7d00d4-0a35-4afb-8b89-3f9d1f966c00',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rails Routing — Resources, Parameters, and Namespace Grouping$escape$,
  $escape$Rails routes live in `config/routes.rb` and are matched top-to-bottom. `resources :articles` generates 7 RESTful routes automatically — index, show, new, create, edit, update, destroy — each mapping to a conventional controller action. Use `only:` or `except:` to trim unused routes and keep `rails routes` output clean.

Route parameters are captured as symbols: `get '/articles/:id', to: 'articles#show'` makes `params[:id]` available in the controller. Constraints scope them further: `constraints(id: /\d+/)` rejects non-numeric ids at the router level, before the controller runs.

Grouping routes under a shared path prefix uses `scope '/api'`, but `namespace :api` goes further — it also expects an `Api::` module prefix on the controller class. Use `namespace` for versioned APIs (`namespace :v1`) and `scope` when you want the URL prefix without the module nesting. Nested `resources` model ownership relationships: `resources :articles do; resources :comments; end` produces `/articles/:article_id/comments`, with both ids available in `params`.$escape$,
  $escape$# config/routes.rb
Rails.application.routes.draw do
  namespace :api do
    namespace :v1 do
      resources :articles, only: [:index, :show, :create] do
        resources :comments, only: [:index, :create]
      end

      get '/search/:query', to: 'search#results',
          constraints: { query: /[^.\/]+/ }
    end
  end

  root 'home#index'
end$escape$,
  $escape$ruby$escape$,
