INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9d7af604-b2cf-42e7-b9e5-f62ee654b46a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rails Project Structure — MVC Default vs. Vertical Slice with Feature Folders$escape$,
  $escape$Rails' default MVC layout (`app/models`, `app/controllers`, `app/services`) collapses under complexity — a 200-model app forces you to hunt across directories for a single feature. Vertical slice architecture fixes this by colocating everything a feature needs under one folder.

Drop a `app/features/` (or `app/domains/`) directory and namespace your classes accordingly. Each slice owns its controller, service object, form object, query object, and serializer. Add the path in `config/application.rb` via `config.autoload_paths << Rails.root.join('app/features')` and Zeitwerk handles the rest — no manual `require` needed.

Slices map cleanly to Rails conventions: controllers still inherit from `ApplicationController`, models stay in `app/models` (they're shared infrastructure), and routes remain in `config/routes.rb` using `namespace :billing` or `scope module: :billing`. This isn't a framework replacement — it's a layering convention on top of Rails. Start vertical slicing when a domain exceeds ~5 controllers or when cross-feature entanglement makes tests brittle.$escape$,
  $escape$# config/application.rb
config.autoload_paths << Rails.root.join('app/features')

# app/features/billing/invoices_controller.rb
module Billing
  class InvoicesController < ApplicationController
    def create
      result = Billing::CreateInvoice.call(invoice_params)
      render json: result, status: :created
    end
  end
end

# config/routes.rb
namespace :billing do
  resources :invoices, only: [:create, :index]
end$escape$,
