INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9e3dfc56-3321-4d18-a140-1fc23fb8c36b',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rails Global Error Handling — Rescue, Render, Repeat$escape$,
  $escape$Rails' `rescue_from` in `ApplicationController` is the idiomatic hook for centralizing error handling across your entire API. Instead of scattering `rescue` blocks through individual controllers, declare handlers once and let Rails dispatch exceptions automatically.

For JSON APIs, pair `rescue_from` with a private `render_error` method that enforces a consistent envelope: `{ error: { code:, message:, details: } }`. This contract lets clients handle errors uniformly without parsing inconsistent shapes.

Map exception classes to HTTP status codes explicitly — don't rely on Rails' default 500 for everything. `ActiveRecord::RecordNotFound` → 404, `ActiveRecord::RecordInvalid` → 422, `ActionController::ParameterMissing` → 400, custom `AuthorizationError` → 403.

For unhandled exceptions, catch `StandardError` as a catch-all last resort and log the full backtrace via `Rails.logger.error` before returning a sanitized 500. Never leak stack traces to clients in production — use `Rails.env.production?` to gate detail exposure.

In Rails 7+, `config.exceptions_app = routes` lets you route exceptions through your own controller for even more control over the response format.$escape$,
  $escape$# app/controllers/application_controller.rb
class ApplicationController < ActionController::API
  rescue_from ActiveRecord::RecordNotFound,       with: :not_found
  rescue_from ActiveRecord::RecordInvalid,        with: :unprocessable
  rescue_from ActionController::ParameterMissing, with: :bad_request
  rescue_from AuthorizationError,                 with: :forbidden
  rescue_from StandardError,                      with: :internal_error

  private

  def render_error(status:, code:, message:, details: nil)
    render json: { error: { code:, message:, details: } }, status:
  end

  def not_found(e)      = render_error(status: :not_found,            code: "NOT_FOUND",      message: e.message)
  def unprocessable(e)  = render_error(status: :unprocessable_entity, code: "INVALID_RECORD", message: e.message, details: e.record&.errors&.full_messages)
  def bad_request(e)    = render_error(status: :bad_request,          code: "BAD_REQUEST",   message: e.message)
  def forbidden(e)      = render_error(status: :forbidden,            code: "FORBIDDEN",     message: e.message)

  def internal_error(e)
    Rails.logger.error("#{e.class}: #{e.message}\n#{e.backtrace&.first(10)&.join("\n")}")
    render_error(status: :internal_server_error, code: "INTERNAL_ERROR", message: Rails.env.production? ? "Something went wrong" : e.message)
  end
end$escape$,
