INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '43421540-252d-4947-9ab0-95d7b3957cbf',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Rails Serialization — camelCase APIs, snake_case Models, and Null Contracts$escape$,
  $escape$Rails models use snake_case everywhere, but JavaScript frontends expect camelCase. Bridging this manually — renaming keys in controllers or `.as_json` overrides — creates drift fast. The clean solution is Alba (or Blueprinter), which centralizes key transformation and null semantics in a dedicated serializer layer.

With `transform_keys :camel_lower`, Alba rewrites every snake_case attribute automatically. No per-field aliasing needed. For null handling, the critical decision is contract stability: don't use `omit_nil` unless bandwidth is a real constraint — omitting nulls forces clients to guard every key access. Instead, be explicit: always emit `null` so the response shape is predictable and TypeScript types stay clean.

For request DTOs, Rails' Strong Parameters already act as your inbound shape contract. Pair `permit` with explicit type coercions (`params[:age].to_i`) rather than relying on implicit casting. This gives you a serialization layer on both sides: Alba out, Strong Parameters in — no extra gem needed for the inbound path.$escape$,
  $escape$# Gemfile: gem 'alba'

class UserSerializer
  include Alba::Resource

  transform_keys :camel_lower

  attributes :id, :email, :created_at

  attribute :full_name { |u| "#{u.first_name} #{u.last_name}" }
  attribute :avatar_url { |u| u.avatar.attached? ? Rails.application.routes.url_helpers.url_for(u.avatar) : nil }
  attribute :bio  # emits null if nil — never omit
end

# Controller
render json: UserSerializer.new(@user).serialize
# => {"id":1,"email":"x@y.com","createdAt":"...","fullName":"...","avatarUrl":null,"bio":null}$escape$,
  $escape$ruby$escape$,
